{title: Ballad Of The Grand Ole Opry}
{artist: George Morgan}
{composer: Written by George Morgan and Tommy Hill}

[C]As the lights were turned off [F]and the curtain was closed
And [C]all of the [D7]songs had been [G7]sung
At the [C]Grand Ole Opry [F]I sat there and wondered
[C]How this great country [G7]show had [C]begun
Did the Great One above us [F]gather some tears
With [C]some heartache [D7]He took from life’s [G7]page
And [C]mix it together [F]with laughter and joy
And [C]sprinkle it [G7]over the [C]stage
Did He speak to the heart [F]of all the great stars
Did [C]He help them put [D7]soul in their [G7]songs
And [C]maybe He guided [F]their foot steps in life
And [C]showed them just [G7]where they [C]belong
Could it be He was thinking [F]one Saturday night
Of [C]something [D7]that we all could [G7]share
So [C]He started the Opry [F]for you and for me
And [C]He put this great [G7]show on the [C]air
Did He know there’d be happiness [F]there on the stage
Did [C]He know men would [D7]cry in the [G7]wings
Is [C]He pleased with the smiles [F]on the faces of thousands
As [C]each star steps [G7]out there and [C]sings
And each Saturday night [F]over forty some years
Folks [C]have lined up for [D7]blocks just to [G7]see
How [C]the Great One has played [F]the best show in the land
On the [C]stage of the [G7]Grand Ole O[C]pry